<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12182a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12182a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12182a"> 182(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Brendan&apos;s willow curragh</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">According to the records, Brendan <font color="green">[Saint Brendan, the Navigator]</font> was not first on this quest. Barinthus, a neighbouring monk, had fared seaward in search of a truant brother and had found him in the island called &ldquo;Delicious&rdquo;, from which they sailed yet farther west and found other wonders. But at all events, however moved, Brendan bade his monks to fast with him forty days, then choosing fourteen of them, he built <mark>a great curragh, with ribs and frame of willow</mark>, hide-covered, and so with forty days of provisions they set out upon the trackless sea, steering for the &ldquo;summer solstice&rdquo; <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGWM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGWM"><cite title="source">Munster</cite></a> (1911) 56-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
